2.â“ Can a try block exist alone?

âŒ NO
âœ… YES only in try-with-resources

Try-with-resources
try (FileReader fr = new FileReader("a.txt")) {
    // code
}


âœ… LEGAL

WHY this is allowed

Because resource management itself is a guaranteed behavior.

Behind the scenes, the compiler rewrites it into:

FileReader fr = new FileReader("a.txt");
try {
    // code
} finally {
    fr.close();
}

ğŸ“Œ So even without catch, there IS a finally-equivalent block
Thatâ€™s why the grammar allows it.

ğŸ‘‰ Key idea

Try-with-resources is NOT just try â€” it is try + implicit finally.